  "slug": "beef-enchiladas",
  "title": "Beef enchiladas",
  "subtitle": "Spiced ground beef in red-chilli sauce, baked under cheese.",
  "excerpt": "Soft tortillas rolled around a filling of cumin-spiced ground beef, laid in a baking dish, smothered in red enchilada sauce, and baked under a blanket of cheese. Tex-Mex Sunday dinner. Feeds six with a green salad.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The Tex-Mex enchilada tradition as it developed in San Antonio and the Rio Grande Valley in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Red chilli sauce technique follows the classic ancho-and-cumin Tex-Mex canon.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The Tex-Mex red enchilada lives on three components: a chilli sauce built from ancho and cumin, a spiced beef filling, and tortillas that absorb both. The sauce goes on the bottom of the dish, around the rolls, and over the top. The cheese melts as a blanket across the surface. The whole thing rests 10 minutes after the oven so the sauce settles.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Corn tortillas are the proper choice but they tear easily when cold; warm them for ten seconds either side in a dry pan first. Flour tortillas roll more forgivingly but the texture is softer in the bake.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
