      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A 30 by 23 cm rectangular baking dish holds 12 rolled enchiladas neatly side by side.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soften the anchos",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Tear the {{ancho-chilli}} of ancho chillies open, shake out the seeds, and tip into a small bowl. Cover with boiling water and weigh down with a saucer. Soak for 20 minutes until soft and pliable.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Drain the soaked chillies. Tip into a blender with {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes, {{garlic}} of garlic, {{cumin-ground}} of cumin, {{oregano-dried}} of oregano, and 200 ml of the {{stock-beef}} stock. Blend until smooth. Heat {{vegetable-oil}} of oil in a saucepan; whisk in {{plain-flour}} of flour and cook for 1 minute to a pale paste. Pour in the chilli purée and the remaining stock. Simmer for 8 minutes until glossy and slightly thickened. Taste and add salt.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the beef",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{vegetable-oil}} of oil in a wide frying pan over medium-high. Add {{onion}} of chopped onion and cook for 5 minutes until soft. Stir in {{garlic}} of chopped garlic for 30 seconds. Add {{beef-mince}} of beef and break apart with a wooden spoon. Cook for 8 minutes until any liquid has cooked away and the beef is starting to brown. Stir in {{cumin-ground}} of cumin, {{chilli-powder}} of chilli powder, {{oregano-dried}} of oregano, and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Ladle in 4 tablespoons of the enchilada sauce to bind the filling.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Assemble",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 180°C. Pour a third of the enchilada sauce across the base of the dish. Warm the tortillas one by one in a dry pan, 10 seconds a side. Lay a tortilla on the worktop, spoon two tablespoons of beef across the middle, roll up tightly and place seam down in the dish. Continue with the rest. Pour the remaining sauce evenly over the top. Scatter {{cheddar}} of grated cheddar across the lot.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake for 25 minutes until the cheese is melted, bubbling, and starting to brown at the edges. Rest 10 minutes before serving. Scatter with chopped coriander if using.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Warm each tortilla in a dry pan for 10 seconds a side immediately before filling. Cold corn tortillas crack; warm ones bend.",
              "cause": "Tortillas too cold and brittle.",
              "symptom": "Tortillas split when rolling"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The flour-oil roux is what gives the sauce body. Simmer for the full 8 minutes after the purée goes in.",
              "cause": "Roux step skipped, or sauce not simmered long enough.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use the full third of the sauce on top. The tortillas need to drink some of the sauce as they bake.",
              "cause": "Not enough sauce poured over before the cheese.",
              "symptom": "Enchiladas dry on top"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Rest the dish 10 minutes after pulling from the oven. The cheese sets enough to hold the rolls together when lifted.",
              "cause": "Enchiladas not rested.",
              "symptom": "Filling falls out when serving"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Beef enchiladas are the centre of the Tex-Mex Sunday plate, served alongside refried beans, rice, and a small heap of shredded lettuce dressed with lime. The cheese-blanketed Tex-Mex version splits from the Mexican enchiladas of Oaxaca and Puebla, which lean towards mole sauce and a lighter cheese crumble. Both are right; the Tex-Mex one is what you crave on a cold Friday night.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
